0. Background

Now that we have called and exported genotypes at the lineage level, let's filter invididuals based on missingness before we proceed with detecting sex-linked loci.

2. Filter individuals by call rate

Let's calculate call rate for each individual.

CallRate <- lapply(my.dfs, function(x){
  #sum the number of "-1" for each row, divide by the total
  y <- 1 - rowSums(x[,2:ncol(x)]=="-1")/(ncol(x)-1)
  
  #make a dataframe with sample name and call rate
  y <- tibble("sampleID"=x$sampleID,
              "callRate"=as.numeric(y))
  
  return(y)
})

Add species, population and sex information, which are found in the sample name

CallRate <- lapply(CallRate, function(x){
  y <- x %>% mutate(Species = substr(sampleID,1,4),
                    Pop = substr(sampleID,6,7))
  
  return(y)
})

Plot call rate by individual at the species level as a histogram.

plot2 <- lapply(CallRate, function(x){
  y <- ggplot(x) +
    geom_histogram(aes(x=callRate)) + xlim(0,1) +
    theme_classic()
  
  return(y)
})

3. Assess marker call rate

Transpose the dataset to have individuals as columns.

my.dfs2 <- lapply(my.dfs, function(x){
  y <- as_tibble(t(x),
                 rownames = "row_names") %>%
    row_to_names(row_number = 1)
  
  return(y)
})

Remove all whitespaces produced by t.

my.dfs2 <- lapply(my.dfs2, function(x){
  y <- as_tibble(apply(x, 2, str_remove_all, " "))
  
  return(y)
})

Convert all remaining columns (which include 0,1,2 and -1) to numeric, except for the sampleID column (which actually contains markerIDs)

my.dfs2 <- lapply(my.dfs2, function(x){
  #exclude first 3 rows which contain sampleID, species ID and pop ID.
  y <- x[3:nrow(x),] %>%
  #mutate all but first column to numeric
  mutate_at(vars(-("sampleID")),as.numeric) %>%
  rename(markerID = sampleID)
  
  return(y)
})

Calculate marker call rate

CallRate2 <- lapply(my.dfs2, function(x){
  y <- 1 - rowSums(x[,2:ncol(x)]=="-1")/(ncol(x)-1)
  
  y <- tibble("markerID"=x$markerID,
              "callRate"=as.numeric(y))
  
  return(y)
})

Plot as histogram to assess distribution

plot3 <- lapply(CallRate2, function(x){
  y <- ggplot(x) + geom_histogram(aes(x=callRate),
                                  bins=100) + theme_bw()
  
  return(y)
})

I will not filter markers at this stage, as analyses of sex-linkage will include a filter for call rate later on (especially because some of those low call rate could be sex specific in a single species and for biological females, which are present in lower numbers in the dataset).

rm(CallRate2, my.dfs2)

What I will do on the other hand is to retain one sample per individual (we currently have multiple technical replicates for ~15% of individuals).

Add column to denote replicate ID

CallRate <- lapply(CallRate, function(x){
  y <- x %>%
    mutate(replica=str_extract(sampleID, "[^_]+$")) %>%
    mutate(replica=case_when(replica == "a" ~ "a",
                           replica == "b" ~ "b",
                           TRUE ~ "norep"))
  
  return(y)
})

Pivot wider to have one observation per sample, retaining only samples where we have at least one replica.

CallRate2 <- lapply(CallRate, function(x){
  y <- x  %>%
    filter(callRate > 0.65) %>%
    filter(replica != "norep") %>%
    mutate(sampleID = str_remove(sampleID, "_a$|_b$")) %>%
    pivot_wider(names_from = replica, values_from = callRate)
  
  return(y)
})

#also create a vector of all individuals without replicates
#which we want to retain
inds.retain <- lapply(CallRate, function(x){
  y <- x %>%
    filter(callRate > 0.65) %>%
    filter(replica == "norep") %>%
    pull(sampleID)
  
  return(y)
})

Let's assess which replicate has the higher call rate for each sample, and then create a vector containing only those samples with a higher call rate.

inds.retain2 <- lapply(CallRate2, function(x){
  y <- x  %>%
  mutate(best = case_when(is.na(a) == TRUE ~ "b",
                          is.na(b) == TRUE ~ "a",
                          a >= b ~ "a",
                          a < b ~ "b")) %>%
  mutate(sampleID = paste0(sampleID,"_",best))
  
  z <- y %>% pull(sampleID)
  
  return(z)
})

We will also remove LM_M_JC_Kindie5_M and LM_M_JC_lowerKindie1 as they appeared as outliers in the population structure plots.

inds.retain2$LM <- inds.retain2$LM[!inds.retain2$LM %in%
                                  c("LM_M_JC_lowerKindie1_M_a","LM_M_JC_Kindie5_M_a")]

Merge individual IDs for samples with and without replicates that we want to retain

inds.retain <- mapply(function(a,b){
  y <- sort(c(a,b))
  
  return(y)
  
}, inds.retain, inds.retain2)

And finally filter accordingly

my.dfs <- mapply(function(x,y){
  z <- x[(x$sampleID %in% y),]
  
  return(z)
}, my.dfs, inds.retain, SIMPLIFY = FALSE)


tempCR <- mapply(function(x,y){
  z <- as_tibble(x[(x$sampleID %in% y),])
  
  return(z)
}, CallRate, inds.retain, SIMPLIFY = FALSE)

Now, to identify sex-linked markers based on heterozygosity, we will need to transpose to have individuals as columns instead of rows.

Remove pop and species information (retained in the sampleID) and transpose

my.dfs <- lapply(my.dfs, function(x){
  y <-  as_tibble(t(x %>% select(-c("Species","Pop"))),
                   rownames = "row_names")
  
  return(y)
})

Turn first row into column names.

my.dfs <- lapply(my.dfs, function(x){
  y <- x %>% row_to_names(row_number = 1)
  
  return(y)
})

Remove all whitespaces produced by t.

my.dfs <- lapply(my.dfs, function(x){
  y <- as_tibble(apply(x, 2, str_remove_all, " "))
  
  return(y)
})

Convert all remaining columns (which include 0,1,2 and -1) to numeric, except for the sampleID column (which actually contains markerIDs now so let's rename it)

my.dfs <- lapply(my.dfs, function(x){
  y <- x %>%
    mutate_at(vars(-("sampleID")),as.numeric) %>%
    rename(markerID = sampleID)
})

Then we also remove the "_a" and "_b" at the end of sampleIDs.

my.dfs <- lapply(my.dfs, function(x){
  names(x) <- gsub(pattern = "_a",
                     replacement = "",
                     x = names(x))
  
  names(x) <- gsub(pattern = "_b",
                     replacement = "",
                     x = names(x))
  
  return(x)
})

Save the resulting files

We can now use this file to calculate genotype counts in the males and females of each lineage, and use that information to identify sex-linked markers.

5. Concluding remarks

By now yo would have noticed how we were pretty lenient with filtering. For instance, we did not conduct any filtering of the markers by heterozygosity, minor allele counts, call rate, etc.

There are two main reasons for this:

  1. When looking for sex-linked markers, we expect markers in the heteromorphic sex to be all heterozygous. Thus, removing based on heterozygous excess would filter out possibly sex-linked markers. A similar thing is true for high missingness. If a sex-linked marker is present in one sex only and not sequenced at all in the other, it would have high missingness, and would thus be filtered out by call rate filters.

  2. A lot of the "filtering" will be indirectly conducted when searching for sex-linked markers. This is because we will assess what markers match the expected genotype proportions, and by doing so discard any markers with non-biologically meaningfull proportions of missing data and/or heterozygosity.
